node.text:
Rest in peace to the great Richard Stolley, who passed away yesterday at 92. An editor at LIFE and founding editor of People Magazine, Stolley  famously acquired the the Zapruder film.

“Dick Stolley was an essential force at LIFE through some highly influential years,” said Kostya Kennedy, editorial director at LIFE. “His spirit and his sensibility remain part of the active brand and magazine today. Landing the Zapruder films was a seismic event for LIFE, for journalism and for the world. In recent years Dick continued to be a friend of the brand, offering fresh ideas and cogent advice. He loved LIFE, journalism and the business—and that showed. This is a great loss.”

For more on Stolley and his incredible career, click the link in bio.

(1) Richard Stolley, 1975 / 📷 Alfred Eisenstaedt, LIFE Picture Collection
(2) Stolley interviewing Zsa Zsa Gabor after a fire destroyed her Bel Air Home, 1961 /📷Ralph Crane / LIFE Picture Collection

#lifemagazine #journalistlife #mediahistory #alfredeisenstaedt #ralphcrane #zapruderfilm @people #rip

node.text:
The artist Salvador Dalí was born on this day in 1904.

In a 1944 essay for LIFE, the surrealist wrote, "...I have never in my life had a nightmare! On the contrary, at night I always dream of extremely agreeable things, and it is precisely when I am perfectly wide-awake, in broad daylight and in contact with practical life, that my most hallucinatory nightmares have always occurred..."

For more portraits of Dali and our other favorite artists from the LIFE archives, tap the link in bio.

(📷Martha Holmes, 1945/LIFE Picture Collection)

Nicknamed 'The Back,' model and actress Vikki Dougan first graced the cover of LIFE in 1953. The New York Times recently tracked down the mysterious beauty, calling her "a midcentury Emily Ratajkowski or Kim Kardashian..." To learn more about Dougan and to see more of her classic LIFE photos, tap the link in bio.

node.text:
Rest in peace to the great astronaut Michael Collins, who died yesterday at 90. One of the three original Apollo 11 crew members, Collins was, according to a 1969 LIFE profile, "a pleasant man who smiles readily...intelligent and a good deal more subtle and many-layered than he cares to admit..."

To learn more about Collins, and to see LIFE's original Apollo 11 special issue, tap the link in bio.

(📷Ralph Morse, 1969/LIFE Picture Collection)

node.text:
Burlesque star Gypsy Rose Lee fixes her makeup before an NBC radio interview, 1936.

This photo appeared in LIFE's first issue on November 23, 1936. The magazine followed Lee throughout her career, covering her life as a "stripteaser," author, and eventual subject of the 1959 musical 'Gypsy.' 

To find out more about this legend (and her surprising hobby!), tap the link in bio.

(📷Alfred Eisenstaedt/LIFE Picture Collection)

node.text:
From 1926 to 1967, the 'Canadian National School on Wheels'—seven trains with live-in teachers—traveled to and educated children in the rural north.

In 1954, LIFE's Cornell Capa visited one of these train schools and chronicled the teacher and his family. We've tracked down one of the pupils from this story, who called her life on the train "the perfect childhood..."

To find out more, tap the link in bio.

node.text:
"Those who dwell, as scientists or laymen, among the beauties and mysteries of the earth are never alone or weary of life." —Rachel Carson

According to a 1961 LIFE profile, Carson was a "shy and gentle person" whose writing on the environment blended "scientific exactness with poetic beauty." Her 1962 classic 'Silent Spring' catalyzed a popular environmental movement in the United States.

For more on this Earth Day, tap the link in bio.

(📷Alfred Eisenstaedt / LIFE Picture Collection)

#rachelcarson #silentspring #lifemagazine #earthday #environmentalism

node.text:
The legendary educator and activist Mamie Till-Mobley, mother of Emmett Till, waves to a crowd of 15,000 in Harlem, 1955.

In her autobiography 'Death of Innocence: The Story Of The Hate Crime That Changed America', Till-Mobley wrote:

"It is not that I dwell on the past. But the past shapes the way we are in the present and the way we will become what we are destined to become. It is only because I have finally understood the past, accepted it, embraced it, that I can fully live in the moment. And hardly a moment goes by when I don’t think about Emmett, and the lessons a son can teach a mother.”

(📷Grey Villet/LIFE Picture Collection)
